I had a situation where I was changing from looping over the animation to showing the first frame only. My initial attempts failed but after some digging around in Duality I came up with this code:

  this.renderer = this.GameObj.GetComponent<AnimSpriteRenderer>();
  ...
  this.renderer.AnimTime = 0;
  this.renderer.AnimFirstFrame = 0; // reset to first animation frame.
  this.renderer.AnimLoopMode = AnimSpriteRenderer.LoopMode.FixedSingle;

Off the back of this [posting](http://forum.adamslair.net/viewtopic.php?f=4&t=695) it occurs to me that I'm not the only one to struggle with freezing animations. I wonder if a formal method could be added that will accomplish this. This new method (with method documentation) will help new users to freeze animations in an easy, intuitive manner. Probably not urgent but still would be nice to have.

To reproduce this bug:
- Create a new empty project
- Add an empty GameObject
- Save the scene
- Create a component that throws an exception in OnShutdown

``` charp
public class ExceptionThrower : Component, ICmpInitializable
{
    public void OnInit(InitContext context)
    {
    }

    public void OnShutdown(ShutdownContext context)
    {
        throw new NotImplementedException();
    }
}
```
- Add this component to the empty GameObject
- Run the sandbox

If you re-open your scene file, everything will be deleted. This will delete all GameObjects, not just the object containing the component that threw the exception.

Duality makes backups, which kind of protects against this, but I think that it would be better to prevent the saving in the first place if this kind of bug occurs, or at least save all valid GameObjects/Components

See http://forum.adamslair.net/viewtopic.php?f=16&t=669 for the forum post that mentioned this issue.
